The Morning Download: Google Researcher Seeks Breakthrough in Quantum Computing
Good morning. It is said in business, perhaps too often, that you need to focus on where the puck is going, not on where the puck is at any given moment. What if the puck is headed in two directions at once? Could you model for that outcome? If so, you grasp the fundamental weirdness at the heart of quantum computing, in which bits, or qubits, aren’t simply ones or zeroes, but exist in both states at once.  Physicist John Martinis joined Alphabet Inc.’s Google to solve two of the most pressing challenges in advancing this science. “The real excitement is, if you can do it efficiently, you can start solving problems that you couldn’t even dream of solving on a classical computer,” he says.

